name="source">Lang's <fr:link
type="local"
href="lang-2002-algebra.xml"
addr="lang-2002-algebra"
title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 4.1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> be a field, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\leq \mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk )]]></fr:tex> be a finite subgroup of field automorphisms. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}=\Bbbk ^{H}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-002W.xml"
addr="nt-002W"
title="Size of finite subgroup of field automorphisms is not greater than index of subfield fixed by the subgroup">subfield fixed by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex></fr:link>, then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[|H|\leq [\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}].]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1115</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#375</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-375.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=|H|]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m=[\Bbbk  : \mathbb {F}]]]></fr:tex>. Either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\leq  m]]></fr:tex> (as desired) or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n>m]]></fr:tex> (which we want to prove leads to contradiction).</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 1:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\leq  m]]></fr:tex>. This is the desired case, and we have the result.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Case 2:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n>m]]></fr:tex> (i.e., there are more automorphisms than there are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>-linarly independent elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>). Given <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ^{m}]]></fr:tex> with components <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha =(\alpha _{1},…,\alpha _{m})]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \in  H]]></fr:tex> be arbitrary. We write for the componentwise application of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> as:
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\sigma \alpha =(\sigma \alpha _{1},…,\sigma \alpha _{m}).]]></fr:tex>
Then for the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\{\sigma _{1},…,\sigma _{n}\},]]></fr:tex> we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma _{1}\alpha ]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma _{n}\alpha ]]></fr:tex> gives the basis for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ^{n}]]></fr:tex>: there exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c_{i}\in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[c_{1}\sigma _{1}\alpha +…+c_{n}\sigma _{n}\alpha =0.]]></fr:tex>
We write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma =c_{1}\sigma _{1}+…+c_{n}\sigma _{n}]]></fr:tex>. But take <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{1}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{m}]]></fr:tex> as a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>-basis of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>, then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\sigma \alpha _{1}=…=\sigma \alpha _{m}=0]]></fr:tex>
which implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma =0]]></fr:tex>, which contradicts the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-002T.xml"
addr="nt-002T"
title="Linear Independence of Characters">linear independence of characters</fr:link>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
