name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link
type="local"
href="dummit-2004-abstract.xml"
addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Proposition 13.4.30</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a field. Then there exists an algebraically closed field <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> containing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>985</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#407</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-407.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof (Jelonek 1993)</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>21</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> be a field such that
<fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}\subseteq \mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex>, and</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathbb {L}| > \max (|\mathbb {F}|,\aleph _{0})=:\mathcal {N}]]></fr:tex> (to ensure <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> is a set, not a proper class).</fr:li></fr:ol>
Then we can turn this into a lattice with ordering given by inclusion. Then by <fr:link
type="local"
href="zorn's-lemma.xml"
addr="zorn's-lemma"
title="Zorn's lemma">Zorn's lemma</fr:link>, there exists a maximal element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex> which we will prove is the algebraic closure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="nst-002J.xml"
addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>: Assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex> is not an algebraic closure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a nonconstant polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\in  L_{0}[x]]]></fr:tex> which has no root in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists an algebraic extension <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex> which has a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> (say, the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-001S.xml"
addr="nt-001S"
title="Splitting Field of a Polynomial">splitting field</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex>). Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> is an algebraic extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|L_{0}|\leq |W|\leq \mathcal {N}]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|S\setminus  L_{0}|=|S|>|W\setminus  L_{0}|]]></fr:tex>. So there exists an injection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i\colon  W\to  S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i(x)=x]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  L_{0}]]></fr:tex>. If we induce by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> an algebraic structure from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> onto <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i(W)]]></fr:tex> we obtain a new maximal element of the lattice which is greater than <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex>, giving us our contradiction. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[L_{0}]]></fr:tex> must be an algebraic closure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 

 
   
