title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(1) <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180504093511/http://www2.im.uj.edu.pl/actamath/PDF/30-131-132.pdf">Jelonek proved this in 1993</fr:link>, which cleaned up a more sloppy version of the same proof by Artin. Lang's <fr:link
type="local"
href="lang-2002-algebra.xml"
addr="lang-2002-algebra"
title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link> (Theorem V.2.6 and its Corollary) follows Artin's proof, as well, but carefully patches it. In fact, it seems Lang's approach has become more or less standard.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(2) Jelonek's proof also establishes that the cardinality of the algebraic closure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\max (|\mathbb {F}|,\aleph _{0})]]></fr:tex>. In particular, the algebraic closure is always infinite.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
