type="machine">#404</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-404.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof (Lang)</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>21</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be the set of all pairs <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F,\tau )]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is a subfield of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> containing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau ]]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> to an embedding of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau \colon  F\hookrightarrow \mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> (where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau |_{\mathbb {F}}=i]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
<fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F,\tau )]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F',\tau ')]]></fr:tex> are such pairs, we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F,\tau )\leq (F',\tau ')]]></fr:tex> if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F\subseteq  F']]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau '|_{F}=\tau ]]></fr:tex>. Note: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is not empty (it contains <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathbb {F},i)]]></fr:tex>) and it is inductively ordered: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F_{i},\tau _{i})]]></fr:tex> is a totally ordered subset, we let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F=\bigcup  F_{i}]]></fr:tex> and define <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> to be equal to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau _{i}]]></fr:tex> on each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{i}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(F,\tau )]]></fr:tex> is an upper bound for the totally ordered subset. Using <fr:link
type="local"
href="zorn's-lemma.xml"
addr="zorn's-lemma"
title="Zorn's lemma">Zorn's lemma</fr:link>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,\lambda )]]></fr:tex> be a maximal element in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda ]]></fr:tex> is an extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, and the claim is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K=\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>. Otherwise there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \notin  K]]></fr:tex>. But our embedding <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda ]]></fr:tex> has an extension to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K(\alpha )]]></fr:tex> thereby contradicting the maximality of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,\lambda )]]></fr:tex>. This proves there exists an extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>. We will just abuse notation and denote this extension by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> again.</fr:p>
<fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is algebraically closed and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> is algebraic over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i(\Bbbk )]]></fr:tex> is algebraically closed and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}]]></fr:tex> is algebraic over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i(\Bbbk )]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {L}=i(\Bbbk )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
